{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-96d1daca5b85417a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tFrom Read Speech to Spoken Digits: A Task-Specific Evaluation of Speech\n2\tPrivacy With Informed Attackers\n3\tJule Pohlhausen ID 1,2,∗∗ , Anjana Rajasekhar3 , Anna Leschanowsky ID 3 , Joerg Bitzer ID 1\n4\t1\n5\t\n6\tInstitute of Hearing Technology and Audiology, Jade University of Applied Sciences, Oldenburg,\n7\tGermany\n8\t2\n9\tDept. of Medical Physics and Acoustics, Carl von Ossietzky Universität Oldenburg, Germany\n10\t3\n11\tFraunhofer Institute for Integrated Circuits (IIS), Erlangen, Germany\n12\tjule.pohlhausen@jade-hs.de\n13\t\n14\tarXiv:2607.21393v1 [eess.AS] 23 Jul 2026\n15\t\n16\tAbstract\n17\tProtecting speech privacy in real-life audio recordings is a growing concern. This contribution evaluates the effectiveness of\n18\tthree obfuscation techniques in protecting linguistic speech content, using digit recognition as a task-specific and practically\n19\tmotivated evaluation scenario. As a first baseline, a generalpurpose speech recognition model and a digit-specific classifier were applied as informed attackers to recognise both single digits and concatenated digit sequences. Our experimental\n20\tresults demonstrate significant differences in recognition performance across digit modality, speech rate, and attack model.\n21\tThese findings emphasize the need for more comprehensive and\n22\tapplication-oriented evaluation methods to ensure speech privacy.\n23\tIndex Terms: speech privacy, speech recognition, digit recognition, obfuscation, privacy evaluation\n24\t\n25\t1. Introduction\n26\tIn many areas of everyday life, audio recordings have become\n27\tan integral part of data collection and automated analysis. Examples include monitoring in smart homes [1] or elder care facilities [2], acoustic surveillance systems [3], and the analysis\n28\tof social behaviour [4]. In particular, speech recordings constitute a rich source of personal, sensitive information, encompassing named entities (persons, dates, locations, organizations,\n29\tetc.), medical details, political opinions, and paralinguistic attributes such as the speaker’s gender or health status [5, 6]. Consequently, voice recordings and speech data are considered personal data under the European general data protection regulation\n30\t(GDPR) and require proper protection from misuse [7].\n31\tA common attack scenario assumes that a potential attacker\n32\thas unauthorised access to audio recordings and seeks to exploit sensitive information. While the VoicePrivacy Challenges\n33\t(VPC) [8, 9] have promoted the development of safeguards targeting speaker-related voice attributes, this contribution focuses\n34\ton content-related sensitive information as a complementary direction. With the increasing power and availability of automatic\n35\tspeech recognition (ASR) systems, the risk of sensitive information being exploited has grown. To mitigate this threat and ensure the protection of linguistic speech content, various privacypreserving techniques have been proposed, including obfuscation, content masking, encryption, adversarial learning, and distributed learning [10, 11, 12, 13]. Apparently, the concealment\n36\tof linguistic content must be achieved while maintaining the\n37\tutility of the signal for downstream tasks, resulting in a tradeoff between privacy and utility. For instance, obfuscation techniques with low computational complexity apply temporal and\n38\tspectral smoothing [14], resampling [15], or sound shredding\n39\t[16] to conceal linguistic content and simultaneously retain suf** indicates the corresponding author.\n40\t\n41\tficient utility for tasks such as conversation analysis or audiobased activity recognition. Such light-weighted methods are\n42\tparticularly relevant for resource-constrained edge devices, such\n43\tas smart home sensors or wearable recording systems, where\n44\tprivacy-preserving processing must be performed locally prior\n45\tto any transmission or cloud-based analysis.\n46\tMost evaluations of ASR performance have relied on read\n47\tspeech and the word error rate (WER) as the primary evaluation metric [17, 18, 9, 14]. However, the WER treats all words\n48\tas equally important, whereas in practice only a small subset\n49\tof words carries sensitive information. This motivates a shift\n50\ttowards task-specific evaluation, where the attack model is tailored to a specific category of sensitive information rather than\n51\tgeneral speech content. Digits represent a particularly wellsuited target for such an evaluation for several reasons. First,\n52\tnumerical information such as phone numbers, bank account\n53\tnumbers, credit card numbers, and transaction authentication\n54\tnumbers (TAN) is among the most directly exploitable sensitive\n55\tinformation in speech recordings, with immediate consequences\n56\tfor financial security and personal privacy. Second, digits form\n57\ta closed, well-defined vocabulary of ten classes, enabling controlled evaluation with clearly interpretable error rates. Third,\n58\tunlike read speech, digit sequences impose a strict ordering constraint, where a single recognition error may render the entire\n59\tsequence unusable, making the evaluation particularly sensitive\n60\tto obfuscation effectiveness.\n61\tThe proposed evaluation assumes that a potential attacker\n62\tsuccessfully identified segments containing digit sequences in\n63\t(long-term) recordings – for instance, using voice activity detection (VAD) or keyword spotting – and subsequently applies\n64\teither a general-purpose ASR model or a digit-specific classifier\n65\tfor recognition. With accuracies exceeding 95 % for recognising\n66\tisolated digits with various architectures [19, 20, 21], the recognition of digit sequences can be addressed by first segmenting\n67\tthe sequence into individual digits and subsequently applying\n68\tsingle digit recognition. Due to data availability, the evaluation\n69\tis restricted to digits from zero to nine, but serves as a foundation\n70\tfor further research that might consider multi-digit numbers, dialects, and disfluencies. Further, the considered optimal attack\n71\tconditions represent the strongest privacy concern. To the best\n72\tof the authors’ knowledge, this work presents the first evaluation of the robustness of current obfuscation techniques against\n73\ttargeted digit recognition attacks with informed models. In this\n74\tinformed scenario, the attacker has complete knowledge of the\n75\tobfuscation technique and its parameters, and trains or finetunes\n76\tmodels on obfuscated data [22]. The remainder systematically\n77\tanalyses the impact of digit modality, speech rate, and attack\n78\tmodel choice on the digit recognition performance.\n79\t\n80\t2. Experimental setup\n81\tExperiments were performed on two Nvidia RTX 3090 Ti\n82\tGPU and one Intel Alder Lake CPU, based on the open-source\n83\t\n84\t\fTable 1: Total WER in % on LibriSpeech test-clean [24]: Tested with informed ASR models for temporal smoothing and resampling,\n85\twhile the original ASR model was applied for shredding.\n86\tOriginal\n87\t80 Mel [14]\n88\t2.34\n89\t\n90\tTemporal smoothing [14]\n91\t125 ms 250 ms 375 ms 500 ms\n92\t\n93\tResampling [15]\n94\t800 Hz 500 Hz 320 Hz\n95\t\n96\t500 ms\n97\t\n98\t5.97\n99\t\n100\t27.55\n101\t\n102\t102.60\n103\t\n104\t32.90\n105\t\n106\t78.43\n107\t\n108\t102.76\n109\t\n110\tspeech-processing toolkit SpeechBrain [23]. The experimental\n111\tframework is publicly available1 [14], including scripts for training, inference, and evaluation.\n112\t2.1. Obfuscation techniques\n113\tThree methods based on signal processing were evaluated for\n114\ttheir ability to protect linguistic content with low computational\n115\tcomplexity: (1) Temporal smoothing with subsampling reduces\n116\tthe temporal resolution of the signal [25, 14]. This evaluation\n117\tconsidered smoothing times τ = 125, 250, 375, and 500 ms\n118\twith corresponding subsampling factors. (2) Resampling restricts audio signals to low-frequency content [15]. We evaluated downsampling rates of 800, 500, and 320 Hz. The test\n119\tsignals were resampled using torchaudio with anti-aliasing\n120\tfiltering [26]. (3) The shredding approach [16] segments the audio signal into fixed-length blocks, randomises their order, and\n121\tconcatenates the shuffled blocks to reconstruct an audio signal.\n122\tIn this evaluation, fixed block lengths of 100, 200, and 500 ms\n123\thave been used.\n124\t2.2. Attack models for digit recognition\n125\tOur evaluation differentiates between ASR-based and digitspecific attack models. A state-of-the-art general-purpose ASR\n126\tsystem2 was applied, which relies on 80-dimensional log Mel\n127\tfilterbank energies computed on time segments with a window\n128\tsize of 25 ms and a hop size of 10 ms. Since we assume informed attackers, the transformer-based ASR model was finetuned on the LibriSpeech train-clean-360 dataset [24] for each\n129\tparameter of the first two obfuscation techniques. For shredding, the original ASR model was applied, since an informed attacker would potentially try to rearrange the fixed-length blocks\n130\tto reconstruct the original signal. For all utilised obfuscation\n131\ttechniques, Table 1 summarises the total WER on LibriSpeech\n132\ttest-clean [24] as a general baseline for protecting read speech.\n133\tDue to the unavailability of previous approaches to classify\n134\tsingle digits explicitly, as the code was outdated or not publicly\n135\tavailable [19, 20, 21], a deep neural network (DNN) with low\n136\tcomplexity was trained [27]. This DNN operates on the mean\n137\tand variance of 13 Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients (MFCC),\n138\taggregated over time. Its architecture consists of three fully\n139\tconnected layers, each containing 128 neurons with ReLU activation, followed by a softmax output layer with ten classes.\n140\tWith only 37770 learnable parameters, the model was trained\n141\twith a batch size of 32 using the Adam optimiser with sparse\n142\tcategorical cross-entropy as the loss function, converging after ten epochs. The DNN-based approach is intended to be efficient under optimal attack conditions and straightforward to\n143\timplement1 , thereby reducing the burden on potential attackers.\n144\t2.3. Datasets\n145\tThe evaluation utilises two well-established datasets in English:\n146\tAudioMNIST [19] and Google Speech Commands (GSC) digits (v0.0.1) [28]. Table 2 summarises general statistics for both\n147\t1 Code available at https://github.com/ol-MEGA/ppca.\n148\tgit\n149\t2 https://huggingface.co/speechbrain/\n150\tasr-transformer-transformerlm-librispeech\n151\t\n152\t52.15\n153\t\n154\t86.91\n155\t\n156\tShredding\n157\t200 ms 100 ms\n158\t125.30\n159\t\n160\t153.85\n161\t\n162\tdatasets. AudioMNIST contains 50 recordings per speaker and\n163\tdigit, while the GSC digits provide a more unbalanced distribution, with only 164 out of 1847 speakers having recorded all\n164\tten digits. The recording setup for AudioMNIST was more controlled, resulting in cleaner recordings but less speaker variation\n165\tcompared to the GSC digits dataset.\n166\tIn realistic scenarios, sensitive numerical information often appears as digit sequences rather than isolated digits, such\n167\tas phone or bank account numbers. To simulate this, ten digits spoken by the same speaker were concatenated into a single sequence, inspired by the typical length of phone numbers\n168\t[29]. For concatenation, we selected AudioMNIST as it provides a consistent number of recordings per speaker and digit.\n169\tBy varying the silence duration inserted between each digit –\n170\tspecifically 100, 200, and 500 ms – we effectively controlled\n171\tthe speech rate, without altering the speech rate of the original\n172\tdigits. One hypothesis is that these concatenated sequences possibly provide contextual information, which improves the ASRbased digit recognition. Moreover, we expect that a higher silence duration, corresponding to a lower speech rate, will improve digit recognition for temporal smoothing, as the increased\n173\ttime gap between digits prevents smearing of consecutive digits.\n174\tSince the DNN is designed to process single digits, the obfuscated digit sequences were segmented based on the oracle signal boundaries and classified separately. In practice, an attacker\n175\twould need to estimate these boundaries using VAD or forced\n176\talignment; however, oracle boundaries were assumed here to\n177\tprovide an upper bound on recognition performance under optimal attack conditions, isolating the effect of obfuscation from\n178\tsegmentation errors.\n179\tTable 2: Statistics of AudioMNIST [19] and GSC digits [28].\n180\tDataset\n181\tNr. of speakers\n182\tTotal recordings\n183\tTest recordings\n184\tMin. - Max. signal dur. in s\n185\tMedian signal dur. in s\n186\t\n187\tAudioMNIST\n188\t\n189\tGSC\n190\t\n191\t60\n192\t30000\n193\t6000\n194\t0.29 - 1.00\n195\t0.63\n196\t\n197\t1847\n198\t23666\n199\t2552\n200\t0.37 - 1.00\n201\t1.00\n202\t\n203\t2.4. Evaluation metrics\n204\tTo facilitate comparisons with previous work [9, 14], we determined the word error rate (WER), defined as the sum of substitutions, insertions, and deletions in the ASR transcript relative to the total number of tokens in the ground-truth transcript.\n205\tHowever, for single digits, the WER may not accurately reflect\n206\tthe digit recognition performance due to insertions of irrelevant\n207\twords in the ASR transcript. To address this limitation, we introduce the digit recognition error rate (DRER), which compares\n208\tthe aligned ASR hypothesis with the reference digit only. The\n209\tDRER is evaluated using exact and fuzzy matching, where the\n210\tlatter considers a transcript with a Levenshtein distance [30] ≤ 2\n211\tas correct. This threshold was motivated by a preliminary analysis of common ASR confusions, such as substituting two with\n212\tto or too. To avoid inflating performance estimates due to fuzzy\n213\tmatching, duplicate hypotheses occurring across multiple digits,\n214\tand unrelated hypotheses (and, here, him, I, in, it, no, non, oh, or, s,\n215\t\n216\t\f\u0000:\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n217\t\n218\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n219\t\u0000'\u0000D\u0000W\u0000D\u0000V\u0000H\u0000W\n220\t\n221\t\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\n222\t\n223\t\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n224\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n225\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n226\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n227\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n228\t\n229\t\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\n230\t\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\n231\t\n232\t\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000I\u0000X\u0000]\u0000]\u0000\\\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n233\t\n234\t\u0000\u0013\n235\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n236\t\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\n237\t\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\n238\t\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\n239\t\u0000\u0013\n240\t\n241\t\u0000\u0013\n242\t\n243\t\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\n244\t\n245\t\u0000\u0017\u0000\u0013\n246\t\u0000\u0019\u0000\u0013\n247\t\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000H\u0000[\u0000D\u0000F\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n248\t\n249\t\u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\n250\t\n251\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n252\t\n253\tFigure 1: WER and DRER with exact and fuzzy matching for informed ASR models on GSC digits [28] and AudioMNIST (AM)\n254\t[19], evaluated for single and concatenated digits with varying\n255\tsilence durations, across different obfuscation parameters.\n256\tsaid, say, so, some, the, there, tim, you) were considered incorrect.\n257\t\n258\tThe DRER was calculated per speaker as the number of incorrectly recognised digits divided by the total number of digits.\n259\tWe report the DRER averaged across speakers, along with 95 %\n260\tconfidence intervals estimated via bootstrapping [31].\n261\t\n262\t3. Results and discussion\n263\t3.1. ASR-based attack models\n264\tThe comparison of evaluation metrics in Figure 1 reveals that the\n265\tDRER is consistently lower than the WER, since it ignores insertion errors. This difference remains stable for single (cf. purple and blue dots) and concatenated digits, as the insertion rate is\n266\tsimilar for both modalities at higher obfuscation degrees. However, neither metric seems ideal for digit sequences: The WER\n267\tpenalises inserted digits and non-digit tokens equally, while the\n268\tDRER ignores insertions entirely, although they may alter the\n269\trecognised sequence. Both limitations are inherent to temporally ordered entities. Future work will incorporate word-level\n270\t\n271\t\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000H\u0000[\u0000D\u0000F\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n272\t\n273\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n274\t\n275\ttimestamps and confidence scores to assess relevant errors.\n276\tMoreover, fuzzy matching reduces the DRER in Figure 1\n277\ton average by 11.08 % for single compared to 1.37 % for concatenated digits. This difference suggests that the recognition of\n278\tsingle digits is more prone to substitution errors, whereas ASR\n279\tmodels seem to benefit from contextual information within a sequence of concatenated digits, making the additional tolerance\n280\tof fuzzy matching less impactful. Due to space constraints, the\n281\tfollowing figures report the stricter DRER with exact matching,\n282\tas fuzzy matching allows for more uncertainty.\n283\tFigure 2 compares the different obfuscation techniques for\n284\tboth digit modalities and the influence of speech rate. As expected, the DRER increases with higher smoothing times τ ,\n285\tlower sampling rates, and lower shredding block lengths, reflecting the general trends on LibriSpeech test-clean (cf. Table 1). For the original, smoothed, and resampled single digits,\n286\tthe DRER in Figure 2 is consistently lower on the GSC dataset\n287\tcompared to AudioMNIST, which is unexpected given that AudioMNIST is considered a cleaner dataset. However, it is likely\n288\tthat the presence of accents in combination with the lower number of speakers in AudioMNIST contributes to this difference.\n289\tIn contrast, the shredded single digits show a lower DRER on\n290\tAudioMNIST. We hypothesize that this reflects the lower median signal duration of AudioMNIST relative to the GSC digits,\n291\twhich are predominantly normalised to 1 s, as shown in Table 2.\n292\tA lower signal duration indicates a higher speech ratio, which\n293\tmeans that the main part of the digit remains unaltered during\n294\tshredding and results in better recognition performance.\n295\tFor temporal smoothing and resampling, the DRER is consistently lower for concatenated than for single digits. This finding can be attributed to our hypothesis that the ASR model extracts contextual information from digit sequences. For digit\n296\tsequences with τ = 500 ms, the DRER is up to 62.54 % and\n297\tthe WER up to 51.46 % lower than the WER on LibriSpeech\n298\ttest-clean in Table 1. This suggests that temporal smoothing\n299\tmay be less effective at protecting specific entities compared to\n300\tcontinuous read speech. Conversely, the DRER on resampled\n301\tdigit sequences is higher than or similar to the WER in Table 1,\n302\tpossibly due to the loss of high-frequency spectral cues that are\n303\tcharacteristic of certain English digits, such as the fricatives and\n304\tplosives in six, seven, or three. Overall, these results highlight\n305\tthe importance of conducting realistic and practically relevant\n306\tevaluations of privacy.\n307\tAs expected, the DRER declines significantly with increasing silence duration for temporal smoothing, while resampling\n308\tand shredding protect more independently of silence duration.\n309\tSimilar to the findings on speaker identity [32], this highlights\n310\t\n311\t\u0000\u0003\n312\t\u00007\u0000H\u0000V\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000G\u0000D\u0000W\u0000D\u0000V\u0000H\u0000W\n313\t\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n314\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n315\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n316\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n317\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n318\t\n319\t\u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\n320\t\u0000\u0019\u0000\u0013\n321\t\u0000\u0017\u0000\u0013\n322\t\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\n323\t\u0000\u0013\n324\t\n325\t\u00002\u0000U\u0000L\u0000J\u0000\u0011 \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00005\u00006\n326\t\u00005\u00006\n327\t\u00005\u00006 \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G\n328\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0016\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0016\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n329\t\u00002\u0000E\u0000I\u0000X\u0000V\u0000F\u0000D\u0000W\u0000L\u0000R\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000W\u0000H\u0000F\u0000K\u0000Q\u0000L\u0000T\u0000X\u0000H\n330\t\n331\tFigure 2: DRER with exact matching for informed ASR models on GSC [28] and AudioMNIST (AM) [19], both single and concatenated\n332\tdigits with varying silence durations. The ASR models were tested on unprotected signals (Orig.) and signals obfuscated with temporal\n333\tsmoothing with subsampling (Smooth), resampling (RS), and shredding (Shred). Vertical lines indicate 95 % confidence intervals.\n334\t\n335\t\f\u0000\u0003\n336\t\n337\t(a) Comparison of training and test dataset combinations\n338\t\n339\t\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000H\u0000[\u0000D\u0000F\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n340\t\n341\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n342\t\n343\t\u00007\u0000U\u0000D\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000W\u0000H\u0000V\u0000W\n344\t\u0000G\u0000D\u0000W\u0000D\u0000V\u0000H\u0000W\n345\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000$\u00000\n346\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\n347\t\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000$\u00000\n348\t\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\n349\t\n350\t\u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\n351\t\u0000\u0019\u0000\u0013\n352\t\u0000\u0017\u0000\u0013\n353\t\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\n354\t\u0000\u0013\n355\t\n356\t\u00002\u0000U\u0000L\u0000J\u0000\u0011 \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00005\u00006\n357\t\u00005\u00006\n358\t\u00005\u00006 \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G\n359\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0016\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0016\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n360\t\u00002\u0000E\u0000I\u0000X\u0000V\u0000F\u0000D\u0000W\u0000L\u0000R\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000W\u0000H\u0000F\u0000K\u0000Q\u0000L\u0000T\u0000X\u0000H\n361\t\n362\t\u0000\u0003\n363\t\n364\t(b) Comparison of single and concatenated digits\n365\t\n366\t\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000H\u0000[\u0000D\u0000F\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n367\t\n368\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n369\t\n370\t\u0000'\u0000D\u0000W\u0000D\u0000V\u0000H\u0000W\n371\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n372\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n373\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n374\t\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n375\t\n376\t\u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\n377\t\u0000\u0019\u0000\u0013\n378\t\u0000\u0017\u0000\u0013\n379\t\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\n380\t\u0000\u0013\n381\t\n382\t\u00002\u0000U\u0000L\u0000J\u0000\u0011 \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00005\u00006\n383\t\u00005\u00006\n384\t\u00005\u00006 \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G\n385\t\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0016\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0016\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n386\t\u00002\u0000E\u0000I\u0000X\u0000V\u0000F\u0000D\u0000W\u0000L\u0000R\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000W\u0000H\u0000F\u0000K\u0000Q\u0000L\u0000T\u0000X\u0000H\n387\t\n388\tFigure 3: DRER of DNN models trained on unprotected signals (Orig.) and with temporal smoothing with subsampling (Smooth),\n389\tresampling (RS), and shredding (Shred). The DNN models were trained and tested on AudioMNIST (AM) [19] and GSC digits [28] for\n390\t(a) single and (b) concatenated digits with silence durations of 100, 200, and 500 ms. Vertical lines indicate 95 % confidence intervals.\n391\tthe need for evaluating speech privacy at various speech rates.\n392\t3.2. Digit-specific attack models\n393\tThe DNN-based recognition of single digits in Figure 3a reveals a consistent performance gap across training and test\n394\tdataset combinations. The best performance is observed in the\n395\tmatched condition (trained and tested on AudioMNIST), while\n396\tthe worst results arise from the mismatched condition (AudioMNIST trained, GSC tested). This pattern underscores that an attacker’s success is substantially contingent on access to training\n397\tdata drawn from a distribution similar to the target speech. Notably, for original digits, the best combination is comparable to\n398\tthe performance of previous approaches [19, 20, 21].\n399\tAs expected, shredding has no impact on the recognition of\n400\tsingle digits, with the DRER remaining approximately equivalent to that observed on original, unprotected signals. This result\n401\tis a direct consequence of the DNN models’ input feature, consisting of the mean and variance computed over time. Since\n402\tshredding only reorders temporal blocks, the input feature is\n403\teffectively unchanged, rendering shredding entirely ineffective\n404\tagainst this class of attacker model. Notably, this finding has\n405\tbroader implications for the protection of other short, precisely\n406\tsegmented entities with a limited set of possibilities.\n407\tIn contrast to the DRER of informed ASR models shown\n408\tin Figure 2, the DNN-based recognition of single digits deteriorates less as τ increases or the sampling rate decreases, though\n409\tthe general trend remains consistent. This highlights that under optimal attack conditions, a simple but task-specific attack\n410\t\n411\tmodel can pose a substantial threat to privacy. Conversely,\n412\tthe DNN performed significantly worse than the ASR models\n413\ton concatenated digits obfuscated with temporal smoothing or\n414\tshredding, as shown in Figure 3b. For temporal smoothing, the\n415\tDNN benefits less from an increased silence duration. As the\n416\tDNN-based DRER approaches 90 %, corresponding to chancelevel performance, the DNN models lose discriminative capability when evaluated on shredded digit sequences.\n417\t\n418\t4. Conclusions\n419\tThis article analysed the recognition of single and concatenated\n420\tdigits against informed attacker models. The superior performance of the task-specific DNN on single digits highlights that\n421\teven simple attack models pose a substantial privacy threat under optimal conditions, underscoring the importance of considering a diverse range of informed attack strategies and attacker\n422\tmodels in privacy evaluations. In contrast, for the more realistic\n423\tscenario of digit sequences, the ASR models outperformed the\n424\tDNN for most obfuscation parameters, suggesting that contextual information plays a critical role in successful attacks. Overall, experimental results demonstrate that task-specific metrics\n425\tprovide a more meaningful and practically relevant assessment\n426\tof speech privacy than the WER on read speech alone.\n427\t\n428\t5. Acknowledgements\n429\tThis work was supported by the Graduation program of Jade\n430\tUniversity of Applied Sciences (Jade2Pro 2.0).\n431\t\n432\t\f6. Generative AI Use Disclosure\n433\tDuring the manuscript preparation, the authors used AI-assisted\n434\twriting tools in order to improve language and readability. After\n435\tusing these tools, the authors reviewed and edited the content\n436\tas required and take full responsibility for the content of the\n437\tpublication.\n438\t\n439\t7. References\n440\t[1] D. Hollosi, J. Schröder, S. Goetze, and J.-E. Appell, “Voice activity detection driven acoustic event classification for monitoring\n441\tin smart homes,” in Proc. Int. Symp. Appl. Sci. Biomed. Commun.\n442\tTechnol. (ISABEL), 2010, pp. 1–5.\n443\t[2] H. Yang, R. Dong, R. Guo, Y. Che, X. Xie, J. Yang, and J. Zhang,\n444\t“Real-time acoustic scene recognition for elderly daily routines\n445\tusing edge-based deep learning,” Sensors, vol. 25, no. 6, p. 1746,\n446\t2025.\n447\t[3] G. Valenzise, L. Gerosa, M. Tagliasacchi, F. Antonacci, and\n448\tA. Sarti, “Scream and gunshot detection and localization for\n449\taudio-surveillance systems,” in Proc. IEEE Conf. Adv. Video Signal Based Surveill. (AVSS), 2007, pp. 21–26.\n450\t[4] M. R. Mehl, “The Electronically Activated Recorder (EAR): A\n451\tMethod for the Naturalistic Observation of Daily Social Behavior,” Curr. Dir. Psychol. Sci., vol. 26, no. 2, pp. 184–190, 2017.\n452\t[5] A. Nautsch, A. Jiménez, A. Treiber, J. Kolberg, C. Jasserand,\n453\tE. Kindt, H. Delgado, M. Todisco, M. A. Hmani, A. Mtibaa,\n454\tM. A. Abdelraheem, A. Abad, F. Teixeira, D. Matrouf, M. GomezBarrero, D. Petrovska-Delacrétaz, G. Chollet, N. Evans, T. Schneider, J.-F. Bonastre, B. Raj, I. Trancoso, and C. Busch, “Preserving\n455\tprivacy in speaker and speech characterisation,” Comput. Speech\n456\tand Language, vol. 58, pp. 441–480, 2019.\n457\t[6] J. Williams, J. Yamagishi, P.-G. Noé, C. V. Botinhao, and J.-F.\n458\tBonastre, “Revisiting speech content privacy,” in Proc. Conf. of\n459\tInt. Speech Commun. Assoc. (INTERSPEECH), 2021, pp. 42–46.\n460\t[7] European Parliament and Council, “Regulation (EU) 2016/679 of\n461\tthe European Parliament and of the Council of 27 Apr. 2016 on\n462\tthe Protection of Natural Persons With Regard to the Processing\n463\tof Personal Data and on the Free Movement of Such Data, and\n464\tRepealing Directive 95/46/EC (General Data Protection Regulation),” 2016.\n465\t[8] N. Tomashenko, X. Wang, E. Vincent, J. Patino, B. M. L. Srivastava, P.-G. Noé, A. Nautsch, N. Evans, J. Yamagishi, B. O’Brien,\n466\tA. Chanclu, J.-F. Bonastre, M. Todisco, and M. Maouche, “The\n467\tVoicePrivacy 2020 Challenge: Results and findings,” Comput.\n468\tSpeech and Language, vol. 74, 2022.\n469\t[9] M. Panariello, N. Tomashenko, X. Wang, X. Miao, P. Champion,\n470\tH. Nourtel, M. Todisco, N. Evans, E. Vincent, and J. Yamagishi,\n471\t“The VoicePrivacy 2022 Challenge: Progress and Perspectives\n472\tin Voice Anonymisation,” IEEE Trans. Audio, Speech, Language\n473\tProcess., vol. 32, pp. 3477–3491, 2024.\n474\t[10] J. Williams, K. Pizzi, and P.-G. Noé, “Exploratory Evaluation of\n475\tSpeech Content Masking,” in Proc. ITG Conf. on Speech Commun.\n476\tVDE, 2023, pp. 215–219.\n477\t[11] S. Ahmed, A. R. Chowdhury, K. Fawaz, and P. Ramanathan,\n478\t“Preech: A system for {Privacy-Preserving} speech transcription,” in Proc. USENIX Secur. Symp., 2020, pp. 2703–2720.\n479\t[12] T. Bäckström, “Privacy in speech technology,” Proc. IEEE, vol.\n480\t113, no. 7, pp. 668–692, 2025.\n481\t[13] A. Nautsch, A. Jiménez, A. Treiber, J. Kolberg, C. Jasserand,\n482\tE. Kindt, H. Delgado, M. Todisco, M. A. Hmani, A. Mtibaa et al.,\n483\t“Preserving privacy in speaker and speech characterisation,” Comput. Speech and Language, vol. 58, pp. 441–480, 2019.\n484\t[14] J. Pohlhausen, F. Nespoli, and J. Bitzer, “Towards privacypreserving conversation analysis in everyday life: Exploring the\n485\tprivacy-utility trade-off,” Comput. Speech and Language, vol. 95,\n486\tp. 101823, 2026.\n487\t[15] J. Pohlhausen and J. Bitzer, “Revisiting the Privacy of LowFrequency Speech Signals: Exploring Resampling Methods, Evaluation Scenarios, and Speaker Characteristics,” in Proc. Symp. Secur. Privacy Speech Commun. (SPSC), 2025, pp. 85–89.\n488\t\n489\t[16] S. Kumar, L. T. Nguyen, M. Zeng, K. Liu, and J. Zhang, “Sound\n490\tshredding: Privacy preserved audio sensing,” in Proc. Int. Workshop Mobile Comput. Syst. Appl., 2015, pp. 135–140.\n491\t[17] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech:\n492\tAn ASR corpus based on public domain audio books,” in Proc.\n493\tIEEE Int. Conf. on Acoust., Speech and Signal Process. (ICASSP),\n494\t2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n495\t[18] S. Alharbi, M. Alrazgan, A. Alrashed, T. Alnomasi, R. Almojel,\n496\tR. Alharbi, S. Alharbi, S. Alturki, F. Alshehri, and M. Almojil, “Automatic speech recognition: Systematic literature review,”\n497\tIEEE Access, vol. 9, pp. 131 858–131 876, 2021.\n498\t[19] S. Becker, J. Vielhaben, M. Ackermann, K.-R. Müller, S. Lapuschkin, and W. Samek, “AudioMNIST: Exploring explainable\n499\tartificial intelligence for audio analysis on a simple benchmark,”\n500\tJ. Franklin Inst., vol. 361, no. 1, pp. 418–428, 2024.\n501\t[20] R. V. Sharan, “Spoken digit recognition using wavelet scalogram\n502\tand convolutional neural networks,” in Proc. IEEE Recent Adv.\n503\tIntell. Comput. Syst. (RAICS), 2020, pp. 101–105.\n504\t[21] A. M. Tripathi and K. Paul, “When sub-band features meet attention mechanism while knowledge distillation for sound classification,” Appl. Acoust., vol. 195, p. 108813, 2022.\n505\t[22] B. M. L. Srivastava, N. Vauquier, M. Sahidullah, A. Bellet,\n506\tM. Tommasi, and E. Vincent, “Evaluating Voice ConversionBased Privacy Protection against Informed Attackers,” in Proc.\n507\tIEEE Int. Conf. on Acoust., Speech and Signal Process. (ICASSP),\n508\t2020, pp. 2802–2806.\n509\t[23] M. Ravanelli, T. Parcollet, P. Plantinga, A. Rouhe, S. Cornell,\n510\tL. Lugosch, C. Subakan, N. Dawalatabad, A. Heba, J. Zhong,\n511\tJ.-C. Chou, S.-L. Yeh, S.-W. Fu, C.-F. Liao, E. Rastorgueva,\n512\tF. Grondin, W. Aris, H. Na, Y. Gao, R. D. Mori, and Y. Bengio, “SpeechBrain: A General-Purpose Speech Toolkit,” arXiv\n513\tpreprint arXiv:2106.04624, 2021.\n514\t[24] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech:\n515\tAn ASR corpus based on public domain audio books,” in Proc.\n516\tIEEE Int. Conf. on Acoust., Speech and Signal Process. (ICASSP),\n517\t2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n518\t[25] J. Bitzer, S. Kissner, and I. Holube, “Privacy-aware acoustic assessments of everyday life,” J. Audio Eng. Soc. (AES), vol. 64,\n519\tno. 6, pp. 395–404, 2016.\n520\t[26] J. Hwang, M. Hira, C. Chen, X. Zhang, Z. Ni, G. Sun, P. Ma,\n521\tR. Huang, V. Pratap, Y. Zhang, A. Kumar, C.-Y. Yu, C. Zhu,\n522\tC. Liu, J. Kahn, M. Ravanelli, P. Sun, S. Watanabe, Y. Shi, and\n523\tY. Tao, “TorchAudio 2.1: Advancing Speech Recognition, SelfSupervised Learning, and Audio Processing Components for Pytorch,” in Proc. IEEE Autom. Speech Recognit. Understand. Workshop (ASRU), 2023, pp. 1–9.\n524\t[27] P. Bacher, “Audio MNIST digit vocal recognition,” Computer\n525\tsoftware,\n526\thttps://www.kaggle.com/code/paulbacher/\n527\taudio-mnist-digit-vocal-recognition, 2022.\n528\t[28] P. Warden, “Speech commands: A dataset for limited-vocabulary\n529\tspeech recognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1804.03209, 2018.\n530\t[29] World Population Review, “Phone number length by country 2026,” https://worldpopulationreview.com/country-rankings/\n531\tphone-number-length-by-country, [Accessed 22-02-2026].\n532\t[30] V. I. Levenshtein, “Binary codes capable of correcting deletions,\n533\tinsertions, and reversals,” in Sov. Phys.-Dokl., vol. 10, no. 8, 1966,\n534\tpp. 707–710.\n535\t[31] L. Ferrer, O. Scharenborg, and T. Bäckström, “Good practices\n536\tfor evaluation of machine learning systems,” 2024. [Online].\n537\tAvailable: https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.03700\n538\t[32] N. Tomashenko, E. Vincent, and M. Tommasi, “Analysis of speech\n539\ttemporal dynamics in the context of speaker verification and voice\n540\tanonymization,” in Proc. IEEE Int. Conf. on Acoust., Speech and\n541\tSignal Process. (ICASSP), 2025, pp. 1–5.\n542\t\n543\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "84f2f72e-dcfb-46af-a0c9-5c25cc3452cf", "uuid": "e9126fbb-c0f9-4021-ab3e-251d8de3dfe4", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:40:20.932Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.21393v1.txt", "content": "From Read Speech to Spoken Digits: A Task-Specific Evaluation of Speech\nPrivacy With Informed Attackers\nJule Pohlhausen ID 1,2,∗∗ , Anjana Rajasekhar3 , Anna Leschanowsky ID 3 , Joerg Bitzer ID 1\n1\n\nInstitute of Hearing Technology and Audiology, Jade University of Applied Sciences, Oldenburg,\nGermany\n2\nDept. of Medical Physics and Acoustics, Carl von Ossietzky Universität Oldenburg, Germany\n3\nFraunhofer Institute for Integrated Circuits (IIS), Erlangen, Germany\njule.pohlhausen@jade-hs.de\n\narXiv:2607.21393v1 [eess.AS] 23 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract\nProtecting speech privacy in real-life audio recordings is a growing concern. This contribution evaluates the effectiveness of\nthree obfuscation techniques in protecting linguistic speech content, using digit recognition as a task-specific and practically\nmotivated evaluation scenario. As a first baseline, a generalpurpose speech recognition model and a digit-specific classifier were applied as informed attackers to recognise both single digits and concatenated digit sequences. Our experimental\nresults demonstrate significant differences in recognition performance across digit modality, speech rate, and attack model.\nThese findings emphasize the need for more comprehensive and\napplication-oriented evaluation methods to ensure speech privacy.\nIndex Terms: speech privacy, speech recognition, digit recognition, obfuscation, privacy evaluation\n\n1. Introduction\nIn many areas of everyday life, audio recordings have become\nan integral part of data collection and automated analysis. Examples include monitoring in smart homes [1] or elder care facilities [2], acoustic surveillance systems [3], and the analysis\nof social behaviour [4]. In particular, speech recordings constitute a rich source of personal, sensitive information, encompassing named entities (persons, dates, locations, organizations,\netc.), medical details, political opinions, and paralinguistic attributes such as the speaker’s gender or health status [5, 6]. Consequently, voice recordings and speech data are considered personal data under the European general data protection regulation\n(GDPR) and require proper protection from misuse [7].\nA common attack scenario assumes that a potential attacker\nhas unauthorised access to audio recordings and seeks to exploit sensitive information. While the VoicePrivacy Challenges\n(VPC) [8, 9] have promoted the development of safeguards targeting speaker-related voice attributes, this contribution focuses\non content-related sensitive information as a complementary direction. With the increasing power and availability of automatic\nspeech recognition (ASR) systems, the risk of sensitive information being exploited has grown. To mitigate this threat and ensure the protection of linguistic speech content, various privacypreserving techniques have been proposed, including obfuscation, content masking, encryption, adversarial learning, and distributed learning [10, 11, 12, 13]. Apparently, the concealment\nof linguistic content must be achieved while maintaining the\nutility of the signal for downstream tasks, resulting in a tradeoff between privacy and utility. For instance, obfuscation techniques with low computational complexity apply temporal and\nspectral smoothing [14], resampling [15], or sound shredding\n[16] to conceal linguistic content and simultaneously retain suf** indicates the corresponding author.\n\nficient utility for tasks such as conversation analysis or audiobased activity recognition. Such light-weighted methods are\nparticularly relevant for resource-constrained edge devices, such\nas smart home sensors or wearable recording systems, where\nprivacy-preserving processing must be performed locally prior\nto any transmission or cloud-based analysis.\nMost evaluations of ASR performance have relied on read\nspeech and the word error rate (WER) as the primary evaluation metric [17, 18, 9, 14]. However, the WER treats all words\nas equally important, whereas in practice only a small subset\nof words carries sensitive information. This motivates a shift\ntowards task-specific evaluation, where the attack model is tailored to a specific category of sensitive information rather than\ngeneral speech content. Digits represent a particularly wellsuited target for such an evaluation for several reasons. First,\nnumerical information such as phone numbers, bank account\nnumbers, credit card numbers, and transaction authentication\nnumbers (TAN) is among the most directly exploitable sensitive\ninformation in speech recordings, with immediate consequences\nfor financial security and personal privacy. Second, digits form\na closed, well-defined vocabulary of ten classes, enabling controlled evaluation with clearly interpretable error rates. Third,\nunlike read speech, digit sequences impose a strict ordering constraint, where a single recognition error may render the entire\nsequence unusable, making the evaluation particularly sensitive\nto obfuscation effectiveness.\nThe proposed evaluation assumes that a potential attacker\nsuccessfully identified segments containing digit sequences in\n(long-term) recordings – for instance, using voice activity detection (VAD) or keyword spotting – and subsequently applies\neither a general-purpose ASR model or a digit-specific classifier\nfor recognition. With accuracies exceeding 95 % for recognising\nisolated digits with various architectures [19, 20, 21], the recognition of digit sequences can be addressed by first segmenting\nthe sequence into individual digits and subsequently applying\nsingle digit recognition. Due to data availability, the evaluation\nis restricted to digits from zero to nine, but serves as a foundation\nfor further research that might consider multi-digit numbers, dialects, and disfluencies. Further, the considered optimal attack\nconditions represent the strongest privacy concern. To the best\nof the authors’ knowledge, this work presents the first evaluation of the robustness of current obfuscation techniques against\ntargeted digit recognition attacks with informed models. In this\ninformed scenario, the attacker has complete knowledge of the\nobfuscation technique and its parameters, and trains or finetunes\nmodels on obfuscated data [22]. The remainder systematically\nanalyses the impact of digit modality, speech rate, and attack\nmodel choice on the digit recognition performance.\n\n2. Experimental setup\nExperiments were performed on two Nvidia RTX 3090 Ti\nGPU and one Intel Alder Lake CPU, based on the open-source\n\n\fTable 1: Total WER in % on LibriSpeech test-clean [24]: Tested with informed ASR models for temporal smoothing and resampling,\nwhile the original ASR model was applied for shredding.\nOriginal\n80 Mel [14]\n2.34\n\nTemporal smoothing [14]\n125 ms 250 ms 375 ms 500 ms\n\nResampling [15]\n800 Hz 500 Hz 320 Hz\n\n500 ms\n\n5.97\n\n27.55\n\n102.60\n\n32.90\n\n78.43\n\n102.76\n\nspeech-processing toolkit SpeechBrain [23]. The experimental\nframework is publicly available1 [14], including scripts for training, inference, and evaluation.\n2.1. Obfuscation techniques\nThree methods based on signal processing were evaluated for\ntheir ability to protect linguistic content with low computational\ncomplexity: (1) Temporal smoothing with subsampling reduces\nthe temporal resolution of the signal [25, 14]. This evaluation\nconsidered smoothing times τ = 125, 250, 375, and 500 ms\nwith corresponding subsampling factors. (2) Resampling restricts audio signals to low-frequency content [15]. We evaluated downsampling rates of 800, 500, and 320 Hz. The test\nsignals were resampled using torchaudio with anti-aliasing\nfiltering [26]. (3) The shredding approach [16] segments the audio signal into fixed-length blocks, randomises their order, and\nconcatenates the shuffled blocks to reconstruct an audio signal.\nIn this evaluation, fixed block lengths of 100, 200, and 500 ms\nhave been used.\n2.2. Attack models for digit recognition\nOur evaluation differentiates between ASR-based and digitspecific attack models. A state-of-the-art general-purpose ASR\nsystem2 was applied, which relies on 80-dimensional log Mel\nfilterbank energies computed on time segments with a window\nsize of 25 ms and a hop size of 10 ms. Since we assume informed attackers, the transformer-based ASR model was finetuned on the LibriSpeech train-clean-360 dataset [24] for each\nparameter of the first two obfuscation techniques. For shredding, the original ASR model was applied, since an informed attacker would potentially try to rearrange the fixed-length blocks\nto reconstruct the original signal. For all utilised obfuscation\ntechniques, Table 1 summarises the total WER on LibriSpeech\ntest-clean [24] as a general baseline for protecting read speech.\nDue to the unavailability of previous approaches to classify\nsingle digits explicitly, as the code was outdated or not publicly\navailable [19, 20, 21], a deep neural network (DNN) with low\ncomplexity was trained [27]. This DNN operates on the mean\nand variance of 13 Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients (MFCC),\naggregated over time. Its architecture consists of three fully\nconnected layers, each containing 128 neurons with ReLU activation, followed by a softmax output layer with ten classes.\nWith only 37770 learnable parameters, the model was trained\nwith a batch size of 32 using the Adam optimiser with sparse\ncategorical cross-entropy as the loss function, converging after ten epochs. The DNN-based approach is intended to be efficient under optimal attack conditions and straightforward to\nimplement1 , thereby reducing the burden on potential attackers.\n2.3. Datasets\nThe evaluation utilises two well-established datasets in English:\nAudioMNIST [19] and Google Speech Commands (GSC) digits (v0.0.1) [28]. Table 2 summarises general statistics for both\n1 Code available at https://github.com/ol-MEGA/ppca.\ngit\n2 https://huggingface.co/speechbrain/\nasr-transformer-transformerlm-librispeech\n\n52.15\n\n86.91\n\nShredding\n200 ms 100 ms\n125.30\n\n153.85\n\ndatasets. AudioMNIST contains 50 recordings per speaker and\ndigit, while the GSC digits provide a more unbalanced distribution, with only 164 out of 1847 speakers having recorded all\nten digits. The recording setup for AudioMNIST was more controlled, resulting in cleaner recordings but less speaker variation\ncompared to the GSC digits dataset.\nIn realistic scenarios, sensitive numerical information often appears as digit sequences rather than isolated digits, such\nas phone or bank account numbers. To simulate this, ten digits spoken by the same speaker were concatenated into a single sequence, inspired by the typical length of phone numbers\n[29]. For concatenation, we selected AudioMNIST as it provides a consistent number of recordings per speaker and digit.\nBy varying the silence duration inserted between each digit –\nspecifically 100, 200, and 500 ms – we effectively controlled\nthe speech rate, without altering the speech rate of the original\ndigits. One hypothesis is that these concatenated sequences possibly provide contextual information, which improves the ASRbased digit recognition. Moreover, we expect that a higher silence duration, corresponding to a lower speech rate, will improve digit recognition for temporal smoothing, as the increased\ntime gap between digits prevents smearing of consecutive digits.\nSince the DNN is designed to process single digits, the obfuscated digit sequences were segmented based on the oracle signal boundaries and classified separately. In practice, an attacker\nwould need to estimate these boundaries using VAD or forced\nalignment; however, oracle boundaries were assumed here to\nprovide an upper bound on recognition performance under optimal attack conditions, isolating the effect of obfuscation from\nsegmentation errors.\nTable 2: Statistics of AudioMNIST [19] and GSC digits [28].\nDataset\nNr. of speakers\nTotal recordings\nTest recordings\nMin. - Max. signal dur. in s\nMedian signal dur. in s\n\nAudioMNIST\n\nGSC\n\n60\n30000\n6000\n0.29 - 1.00\n0.63\n\n1847\n23666\n2552\n0.37 - 1.00\n1.00\n\n2.4. Evaluation metrics\nTo facilitate comparisons with previous work [9, 14], we determined the word error rate (WER), defined as the sum of substitutions, insertions, and deletions in the ASR transcript relative to the total number of tokens in the ground-truth transcript.\nHowever, for single digits, the WER may not accurately reflect\nthe digit recognition performance due to insertions of irrelevant\nwords in the ASR transcript. To address this limitation, we introduce the digit recognition error rate (DRER), which compares\nthe aligned ASR hypothesis with the reference digit only. The\nDRER is evaluated using exact and fuzzy matching, where the\nlatter considers a transcript with a Levenshtein distance [30] ≤ 2\nas correct. This threshold was motivated by a preliminary analysis of common ASR confusions, such as substituting two with\nto or too. To avoid inflating performance estimates due to fuzzy\nmatching, duplicate hypotheses occurring across multiple digits,\nand unrelated hypotheses (and, here, him, I, in, it, no, non, oh, or, s,\n\n\f\u0000:\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n\u0000'\u0000D\u0000W\u0000D\u0000V\u0000H\u0000W\n\n\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\n\n\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\n\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\n\n\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000I\u0000X\u0000]\u0000]\u0000\\\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n\n\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\n\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\n\u0000\u0013\n\n\u0000\u0013\n\n\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\n\n\u0000\u0017\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0019\u0000\u0013\n\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000H\u0000[\u0000D\u0000F\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n\n\u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\n\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n\nFigure 1: WER and DRER with exact and fuzzy matching for informed ASR models on GSC digits [28] and AudioMNIST (AM)\n[19], evaluated for single and concatenated digits with varying\nsilence durations, across different obfuscation parameters.\nsaid, say, so, some, the, there, tim, you) were considered incorrect.\n\nThe DRER was calculated per speaker as the number of incorrectly recognised digits divided by the total number of digits.\nWe report the DRER averaged across speakers, along with 95 %\nconfidence intervals estimated via bootstrapping [31].\n\n3. Results and discussion\n3.1. ASR-based attack models\nThe comparison of evaluation metrics in Figure 1 reveals that the\nDRER is consistently lower than the WER, since it ignores insertion errors. This difference remains stable for single (cf. purple and blue dots) and concatenated digits, as the insertion rate is\nsimilar for both modalities at higher obfuscation degrees. However, neither metric seems ideal for digit sequences: The WER\npenalises inserted digits and non-digit tokens equally, while the\nDRER ignores insertions entirely, although they may alter the\nrecognised sequence. Both limitations are inherent to temporally ordered entities. Future work will incorporate word-level\n\n\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000H\u0000[\u0000D\u0000F\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n\ntimestamps and confidence scores to assess relevant errors.\nMoreover, fuzzy matching reduces the DRER in Figure 1\non average by 11.08 % for single compared to 1.37 % for concatenated digits. This difference suggests that the recognition of\nsingle digits is more prone to substitution errors, whereas ASR\nmodels seem to benefit from contextual information within a sequence of concatenated digits, making the additional tolerance\nof fuzzy matching less impactful. Due to space constraints, the\nfollowing figures report the stricter DRER with exact matching,\nas fuzzy matching allows for more uncertainty.\nFigure 2 compares the different obfuscation techniques for\nboth digit modalities and the influence of speech rate. As expected, the DRER increases with higher smoothing times τ ,\nlower sampling rates, and lower shredding block lengths, reflecting the general trends on LibriSpeech test-clean (cf. Table 1). For the original, smoothed, and resampled single digits,\nthe DRER in Figure 2 is consistently lower on the GSC dataset\ncompared to AudioMNIST, which is unexpected given that AudioMNIST is considered a cleaner dataset. However, it is likely\nthat the presence of accents in combination with the lower number of speakers in AudioMNIST contributes to this difference.\nIn contrast, the shredded single digits show a lower DRER on\nAudioMNIST. We hypothesize that this reflects the lower median signal duration of AudioMNIST relative to the GSC digits,\nwhich are predominantly normalised to 1 s, as shown in Table 2.\nA lower signal duration indicates a higher speech ratio, which\nmeans that the main part of the digit remains unaltered during\nshredding and results in better recognition performance.\nFor temporal smoothing and resampling, the DRER is consistently lower for concatenated than for single digits. This finding can be attributed to our hypothesis that the ASR model extracts contextual information from digit sequences. For digit\nsequences with τ = 500 ms, the DRER is up to 62.54 % and\nthe WER up to 51.46 % lower than the WER on LibriSpeech\ntest-clean in Table 1. This suggests that temporal smoothing\nmay be less effective at protecting specific entities compared to\ncontinuous read speech. Conversely, the DRER on resampled\ndigit sequences is higher than or similar to the WER in Table 1,\npossibly due to the loss of high-frequency spectral cues that are\ncharacteristic of certain English digits, such as the fricatives and\nplosives in six, seven, or three. Overall, these results highlight\nthe importance of conducting realistic and practically relevant\nevaluations of privacy.\nAs expected, the DRER declines significantly with increasing silence duration for temporal smoothing, while resampling\nand shredding protect more independently of silence duration.\nSimilar to the findings on speaker identity [32], this highlights\n\n\u0000\u0003\n\u00007\u0000H\u0000V\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000G\u0000D\u0000W\u0000D\u0000V\u0000H\u0000W\n\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\n\u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0019\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0017\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0013\n\n\u00002\u0000U\u0000L\u0000J\u0000\u0011 \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00005\u00006\n\u00005\u00006\n\u00005\u00006 \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0016\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0016\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u00002\u0000E\u0000I\u0000X\u0000V\u0000F\u0000D\u0000W\u0000L\u0000R\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000W\u0000H\u0000F\u0000K\u0000Q\u0000L\u0000T\u0000X\u0000H\n\nFigure 2: DRER with exact matching for informed ASR models on GSC [28] and AudioMNIST (AM) [19], both single and concatenated\ndigits with varying silence durations. The ASR models were tested on unprotected signals (Orig.) and signals obfuscated with temporal\nsmoothing with subsampling (Smooth), resampling (RS), and shredding (Shred). Vertical lines indicate 95 % confidence intervals.\n\n\f\u0000\u0003\n\n(a) Comparison of training and test dataset combinations\n\n\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000H\u0000[\u0000D\u0000F\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n\n\u00007\u0000U\u0000D\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000W\u0000H\u0000V\u0000W\n\u0000G\u0000D\u0000W\u0000D\u0000V\u0000H\u0000W\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000$\u00000\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\n\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000$\u00000\n\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\u0000\u0003\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0003\u0000*\u00006\u0000&\n\n\u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0019\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0017\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0013\n\n\u00002\u0000U\u0000L\u0000J\u0000\u0011 \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00005\u00006\n\u00005\u00006\n\u00005\u00006 \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0016\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0016\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u00002\u0000E\u0000I\u0000X\u0000V\u0000F\u0000D\u0000W\u0000L\u0000R\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000W\u0000H\u0000F\u0000K\u0000Q\u0000L\u0000T\u0000X\u0000H\n\n\u0000\u0003\n\n(b) Comparison of single and concatenated digits\n\n\u0000'\u00005\u0000(\u00005\u0000\u0003\u0000H\u0000[\u0000D\u0000F\u0000W\u0000\u0003\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000\b\n\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\n\n\u0000'\u0000D\u0000W\u0000D\u0000V\u0000H\u0000W\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000V\u0000L\u0000Q\u0000J\u0000O\u0000H\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u0000$\u00000\u0000\u0010\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\n\u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0019\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0017\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\n\u0000\u0013\n\n\u00002\u0000U\u0000L\u0000J\u0000\u0011 \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00006\u0000P\u0000R\u0000R\u0000W\u0000K \u00005\u00006\n\u00005\u00006\n\u00005\u00006 \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G \u00006\u0000K\u0000U\u0000H\u0000G\n\u0000\u0014\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0016\u0000\u001a\u0000\u0018\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u001b\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0016\u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000+\u0000] \u0000\u0018\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0015\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V \u0000\u0014\u0000\u0013\u0000\u0013\u0000P\u0000V\n\u00002\u0000E\u0000I\u0000X\u0000V\u0000F\u0000D\u0000W\u0000L\u0000R\u0000Q\u0000\u0003\u0000W\u0000H\u0000F\u0000K\u0000Q\u0000L\u0000T\u0000X\u0000H\n\nFigure 3: DRER of DNN models trained on unprotected signals (Orig.) and with temporal smoothing with subsampling (Smooth),\nresampling (RS), and shredding (Shred). The DNN models were trained and tested on AudioMNIST (AM) [19] and GSC digits [28] for\n(a) single and (b) concatenated digits with silence durations of 100, 200, and 500 ms. Vertical lines indicate 95 % confidence intervals.\nthe need for evaluating speech privacy at various speech rates.\n3.2. Digit-specific attack models\nThe DNN-based recognition of single digits in Figure 3a reveals a consistent performance gap across training and test\ndataset combinations. The best performance is observed in the\nmatched condition (trained and tested on AudioMNIST), while\nthe worst results arise from the mismatched condition (AudioMNIST trained, GSC tested). This pattern underscores that an attacker’s success is substantially contingent on access to training\ndata drawn from a distribution similar to the target speech. Notably, for original digits, the best combination is comparable to\nthe performance of previous approaches [19, 20, 21].\nAs expected, shredding has no impact on the recognition of\nsingle digits, with the DRER remaining approximately equivalent to that observed on original, unprotected signals. This result\nis a direct consequence of the DNN models’ input feature, consisting of the mean and variance computed over time. Since\nshredding only reorders temporal blocks, the input feature is\neffectively unchanged, rendering shredding entirely ineffective\nagainst this class of attacker model. Notably, this finding has\nbroader implications for the protection of other short, precisely\nsegmented entities with a limited set of possibilities.\nIn contrast to the DRER of informed ASR models shown\nin Figure 2, the DNN-based recognition of single digits deteriorates less as τ increases or the sampling rate decreases, though\nthe general trend remains consistent. This highlights that under optimal attack conditions, a simple but task-specific attack\n\nmodel can pose a substantial threat to privacy. Conversely,\nthe DNN performed significantly worse than the ASR models\non concatenated digits obfuscated with temporal smoothing or\nshredding, as shown in Figure 3b. For temporal smoothing, the\nDNN benefits less from an increased silence duration. As the\nDNN-based DRER approaches 90 %, corresponding to chancelevel performance, the DNN models lose discriminative capability when evaluated on shredded digit sequences.\n\n4. Conclusions\nThis article analysed the recognition of single and concatenated\ndigits against informed attacker models. The superior performance of the task-specific DNN on single digits highlights that\neven simple attack models pose a substantial privacy threat under optimal conditions, underscoring the importance of considering a diverse range of informed attack strategies and attacker\nmodels in privacy evaluations. In contrast, for the more realistic\nscenario of digit sequences, the ASR models outperformed the\nDNN for most obfuscation parameters, suggesting that contextual information plays a critical role in successful attacks. Overall, experimental results demonstrate that task-specific metrics\nprovide a more meaningful and practically relevant assessment\nof speech privacy than the WER on read speech alone.\n\n5. Acknowledgements\nThis work was supported by the Graduation program of Jade\nUniversity of Applied Sciences (Jade2Pro 2.0).\n\n\f6. Generative AI Use Disclosure\nDuring the manuscript preparation, the authors used AI-assisted\nwriting tools in order to improve language and readability. After\nusing these tools, the authors reviewed and edited the content\nas required and take full responsibility for the content of the\npublication.\n\n7. References\n[1] D. Hollosi, J. Schröder, S. Goetze, and J.-E. Appell, “Voice activity detection driven acoustic event classification for monitoring\nin smart homes,” in Proc. Int. Symp. Appl. Sci. Biomed. Commun.\nTechnol. (ISABEL), 2010, pp. 1–5.\n[2] H. Yang, R. Dong, R. Guo, Y. Che, X. Xie, J. Yang, and J. Zhang,\n“Real-time acoustic scene recognition for elderly daily routines\nusing edge-based deep learning,” Sensors, vol. 25, no. 6, p. 1746,\n2025.\n[3] G. Valenzise, L. Gerosa, M. Tagliasacchi, F. Antonacci, and\nA. Sarti, “Scream and gunshot detection and localization for\naudio-surveillance systems,” in Proc. IEEE Conf. Adv. Video Signal Based Surveill. (AVSS), 2007, pp. 21–26.\n[4] M. R. Mehl, “The Electronically Activated Recorder (EAR): A\nMethod for the Naturalistic Observation of Daily Social Behavior,” Curr. Dir. Psychol. Sci., vol. 26, no. 2, pp. 184–190, 2017.\n[5] A. Nautsch, A. Jiménez, A. Treiber, J. Kolberg, C. Jasserand,\nE. Kindt, H. Delgado, M. Todisco, M. A. Hmani, A. Mtibaa,\nM. A. Abdelraheem, A. Abad, F. Teixeira, D. Matrouf, M. GomezBarrero, D. Petrovska-Delacrétaz, G. Chollet, N. Evans, T. Schneider, J.-F. Bonastre, B. Raj, I. Trancoso, and C. Busch, “Preserving\nprivacy in speaker and speech characterisation,” Comput. Speech\nand Language, vol. 58, pp. 441–480, 2019.\n[6] J. Williams, J. Yamagishi, P.-G. Noé, C. V. Botinhao, and J.-F.\nBonastre, “Revisiting speech content privacy,” in Proc. Conf. of\nInt. Speech Commun. Assoc. (INTERSPEECH), 2021, pp. 42–46.\n[7] European Parliament and Council, “Regulation (EU) 2016/679 of\nthe European Parliament and of the Council of 27 Apr. 2016 on\nthe Protection of Natural Persons With Regard to the Processing\nof Personal Data and on the Free Movement of Such Data, and\nRepealing Directive 95/46/EC (General Data Protection Regulation),” 2016.\n[8] N. Tomashenko, X. Wang, E. Vincent, J. Patino, B. M. L. Srivastava, P.-G. Noé, A. Nautsch, N. Evans, J. Yamagishi, B. O’Brien,\nA. Chanclu, J.-F. Bonastre, M. Todisco, and M. Maouche, “The\nVoicePrivacy 2020 Challenge: Results and findings,” Comput.\nSpeech and Language, vol. 74, 2022.\n[9] M. Panariello, N. Tomashenko, X. Wang, X. Miao, P. Champion,\nH. Nourtel, M. Todisco, N. Evans, E. Vincent, and J. Yamagishi,\n“The VoicePrivacy 2022 Challenge: Progress and Perspectives\nin Voice Anonymisation,” IEEE Trans. Audio, Speech, Language\nProcess., vol. 32, pp. 3477–3491, 2024.\n[10] J. Williams, K. Pizzi, and P.-G. Noé, “Exploratory Evaluation of\nSpeech Content Masking,” in Proc. ITG Conf. on Speech Commun.\nVDE, 2023, pp. 215–219.\n[11] S. Ahmed, A. R. Chowdhury, K. Fawaz, and P. Ramanathan,\n“Preech: A system for {Privacy-Preserving} speech transcription,” in Proc. USENIX Secur. Symp., 2020, pp. 2703–2720.\n[12] T. Bäckström, “Privacy in speech technology,” Proc. IEEE, vol.\n113, no. 7, pp. 668–692, 2025.\n[13] A. Nautsch, A. Jiménez, A. Treiber, J. Kolberg, C. Jasserand,\nE. Kindt, H. Delgado, M. Todisco, M. A. Hmani, A. Mtibaa et al.,\n“Preserving privacy in speaker and speech characterisation,” Comput. Speech and Language, vol. 58, pp. 441–480, 2019.\n[14] J. Pohlhausen, F. Nespoli, and J. Bitzer, “Towards privacypreserving conversation analysis in everyday life: Exploring the\nprivacy-utility trade-off,” Comput. Speech and Language, vol. 95,\np. 101823, 2026.\n[15] J. Pohlhausen and J. Bitzer, “Revisiting the Privacy of LowFrequency Speech Signals: Exploring Resampling Methods, Evaluation Scenarios, and Speaker Characteristics,” in Proc. Symp. Secur. Privacy Speech Commun. (SPSC), 2025, pp. 85–89.\n\n[16] S. Kumar, L. T. Nguyen, M. Zeng, K. Liu, and J. Zhang, “Sound\nshredding: Privacy preserved audio sensing,” in Proc. Int. Workshop Mobile Comput. Syst. Appl., 2015, pp. 135–140.\n[17] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech:\nAn ASR corpus based on public domain audio books,” in Proc.\nIEEE Int. Conf. on Acoust., Speech and Signal Process. (ICASSP),\n2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n[18] S. Alharbi, M. Alrazgan, A. Alrashed, T. Alnomasi, R. Almojel,\nR. Alharbi, S. Alharbi, S. Alturki, F. Alshehri, and M. Almojil, “Automatic speech recognition: Systematic literature review,”\nIEEE Access, vol. 9, pp. 131 858–131 876, 2021.\n[19] S. Becker, J. Vielhaben, M. Ackermann, K.-R. Müller, S. Lapuschkin, and W. Samek, “AudioMNIST: Exploring explainable\nartificial intelligence for audio analysis on a simple benchmark,”\nJ. Franklin Inst., vol. 361, no. 1, pp. 418–428, 2024.\n[20] R. V. Sharan, “Spoken digit recognition using wavelet scalogram\nand convolutional neural networks,” in Proc. IEEE Recent Adv.\nIntell. Comput. Syst. (RAICS), 2020, pp. 101–105.\n[21] A. M. Tripathi and K. Paul, “When sub-band features meet attention mechanism while knowledge distillation for sound classification,” Appl. Acoust., vol. 195, p. 108813, 2022.\n[22] B. M. L. Srivastava, N. Vauquier, M. Sahidullah, A. Bellet,\nM. Tommasi, and E. Vinc